A wildfire rages in Texas on 27 February 2024. Photo: Greenville Fire-Rescue / Reuters



By Gloria Oladipo 28 February 2024



(The Guardian) – A historic wildfire in Texas continued to rage on Wednesday morning as firefighters work to contain the flames and survey damage.



The Smokehouse Creek fire, the second largest wildfire in Texas to date, has consumed more than 500,000 acres in Texas’s Panhandle area since it ignited on Monday.



The fire is currently at 0% containment, with several Texas counties still evacuated amid growing flames.



The Smokehouse Creek fire began at 40,000 acres on Tuesday, quickly swelling by Wednesday morning, CNN reported. The fire has burned through an area more than half the size of Rhode Island, CNN further reported.



The fire has largely spread given unseasonably warm temperatures and strong wind, propelling flames through dry grassy areas.

description:
Aussies Brace For Icy Weekend



Australians are gearing up for another frigid weekend as rain, wind, and snow sweep in. Melbourne is already experiencing its coldest start to winter in years. While last week, several low-temperature records were shattered across the nation.



Friday morning was particularly chilly in most capital cities.



Sydneysiders woke up to a nippy 7.8C (46F), while Melburnians shivered through their coldest minimum temperatures for the month of June since 2006, with overnight temps averaging 6.6C (43.9F).



Canberra was the country's coldest capital, hitting a freezing -3C (26.6F), a reading among the city's lowest temperatures in years, while Hobart posted a low of 6.4C (43.5F).



Meteorologists warn that temperatures will plunge further as a polar system blows in. This system will start in Western Australia on Friday, move through South Australia and Victoria, and hit New South Wales by Saturday night into Sunday.



Sky News Meteorologist Rob Sharpe pre
title: Aussies Brace For Icy Weekend; Misguided Heat Concerns; The Climate Changes; + Ocean Cooling
